to happen to help change the school system, however, change won't happen immediately until several years after my child has gone through the public school system. At this time, I am paying for my child to get a more attention in the classroom (and after) whereas a classroom full of 30+ kids won't grant my child that same attention and educational push. The public school system seems like an endless ball of yarn that would take forever to straighten out, and that's only if everyone was on the same page.  I have public school teachers that send their children to my child’s private school.  Something has got to be wrong there…  I don’t feel that I am a bad person for feeling this way and that’s why I think tons of parents make sacrifices to get their children better education; it’s not always rich kids. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1119" language="en" documentId="2478" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="MO526" date="Aug 29, 2013 9:43PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="2478" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1119"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>